From 74742abda3c1bb08b958a3784e3773ab95bf8e36 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Gravio <gravio@uni-muenster.de>
Date: Wed, 29 Apr 2026 20:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] qt features form: add n_workers spinbox
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Adds a parallel-workers spinbox to FeatureSubsetExtractorForm so
users can opt into the step-6 parallelization from the UI without
editing code.

Layout decision: the spinbox sits as the last row in the form's
QFormLayout, which the parent OperationForm renders just above the
Run button row. Visually adjacent to the Run button as requested,
without modifying the parent class (no other forms in the workbench
need this hook, so a generic mechanism in OperationForm would be
overkill).

UI behavior:

- Default value: 1 (sequential — byte-equivalent to pre-step-6
  behavior). Existing users see no change unless they touch the
  spinbox.
- Maximum: os.cpu_count() (falls back to 8 if cpu_count returns
  None). On the user's Ryzen 9800X3D, the cap will be 16 (8
  physical cores × 2 SMT threads). Going above physical core count
  rarely helps because the numba kernels are compute-bound, but
  the OS-reported value is the safe ceiling rather than a hard
  policy.
- Suffix: "  worker(s)" so the spinbox reads naturally
  ("4 worker(s)" — the leading double-space is for visual padding).
- Tooltip: explains 1 = sequential, 5-7× speedup typical, and
  flags the verification requirement.
- Hint label below the spinbox: "If n_workers > 1: verify against
  sequential output first via tests/smoke_feature_parallel_verify.py".
  Muted styling (#666, 9pt italic) so it doesn't fight for
  attention but is reachable when the user bumps the spinbox.
  This lives in the form (not just the tooltip) because verification
  matters — wrong feature values from a botched parallel run are
  catastrophically worse than slow correct ones.

Backend wiring:

- collect_args reads self.n_workers.value() and includes it in
  the kwargs dict.
- target() accepts the new n_workers kwarg and passes it through
  to FeatureSubsetsCalculator.

What I considered and rejected:

- A confirmation dialog ("Are you sure you want n_workers > 1?
  Have you verified parallel output?") — too patronizing for a
  research tool used by people who know what they're doing. The
  tooltip + hint label is the right level of friction.
- A new method in OperationForm to inject widgets next to the Run
  button — overkill for a single use case. Putting the spinbox in
  the QFormLayout achieves the same visual placement without
  modifying the parent.
- Capping the spinbox at physical core count via psutil — adds a
  dependency for marginal benefit. os.cpu_count() is good enough.

Test:

- NEW: tests/smoke_qt_n_workers_spinbox.py — 7 cases:
  1. QSpinBox imported from PySide6.QtWidgets
  2. build() instantiates QSpinBox and assigns to self.n_workers
     with min=1, default=1
  3. Maximum is dynamic via os.cpu_count()
  4. collect_args includes 'n_workers' key reading self.n_workers.value()
  5. target() accepts n_workers and passes it through
  6. setToolTip is called with verification mention
  7. Form references smoke_feature_parallel_verify.py so users
     know where to look

Verified in sandbox:
- File compiles
- All 15 smoke tests pass
- AST audit reports zero errors

Stack now at 45 patches:
  44. save_destination_strict     (strict + safe cleanup)
  45. qt_n_workers_spinbox        (this patch)
